                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d31">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.00/562.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Consul General at
                            Shanghai</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName> ([<date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content-and-sibling-dates"
                            calendar="gregorian" when="1911-10-13">undated</date>;] received <hi
                            rend="italic">Oct. 13, 1911</hi>).</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The Hankow situation is more than a mere outbreak. Admiral Sah says that it is
                    the most serious thus far. Chinese sympathy is with the rebels. Japanese-British
                    admirals are on the scene; Japanese prominent; Political situations are
                    possible</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilder.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
